  "prompt": "Can allergies cause dizziness and head pressure?",
  "response": "Yes, allergies can cause dizziness and head pressure. This occurs due to several reasons:\n\n1. Sinus congestion\n- Blocked nasal passages and swollen sinuses can create pressure in the head\n- Inflammation can affect balance and cause dizziness\n\n2. Inner ear effects\n- Allergic reactions can cause fluid buildup in the inner ear\n- This can disrupt the balance mechanism and lead to vertigo or dizziness\n\n3. Eustachian tube dysfunction\n- Allergies can cause swelling that blocks the Eustachian tubes\n- This can create a feeling of fullness or pressure in the head\n\n4. Inflammatory response\n- Allergic reactions trigger histamine release\n- Histamine can cause inflammation and affect blood flow, potentially causing dizziness\n\n5. Medication side effects\n- Some allergy medications can cause dizziness as a side effect\n\n6. Reduced oxygen flow\n- Congestion can limit proper breathing\n- Decreased oxygen can contribute to lightheadedness\n\nIf you're experiencing persistent dizziness or head pressure, it's recommended to consult a healthcare professional to determine the exact cause and appropriate treatment.",
